Title : Séverin Cafferra
Text : [[Image:Severin as Pierrot, c. 1896.jpg|thumb|upright|Séverin as Pierrot, c. 1896, in Séverin, ''L'Homme Blanc'' (Paris, 1929)]][[Image:Poster by Happichy of Severin in Chand d'habits!, 1896.jpg|thumb|upright|Happichy: Séverin in Mendès's ''Chand d'habits!'', poster (1896)]]
<!--[[File:Lucien-Victor Guirand de Scévola.jpg|thumb|Painting of Séverin Cafferra by [[Lucien-Victor Guirand de Scévola]]]]-->

'''Séverin Cafferra''', known as '''Séverin''' or '''mime Séverin'''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://digitalcollections.lib.washington.edu/cdm/ref/collection/social/id/3264 | title=Mime Severin costumed as Pierrot, 1922 | publisher=University of Washington Libraries | date=1922 | accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref> (1863-1930), was one of the best-known French [[Pierrot]]s or [[mime artist]]s around the turn of the twentieth century.

==Life==

Caffera was born in [[Ajaccio]], [[Corsica]].
He studied under the Marseille mime [[Louis Rouffe]] (1849-1885), who in turn had studied under [[Charles Deburau]]. He worked at [[Marseilles]], then at the Théatre des Funambules in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.larousse.fr/encyclopedie/personnage/S%C3%A9verin/138803 | title=Séverin Cafferra, dit Séverin | publisher=Larousse | accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref> In his 1929 book, ''L'Homme Blanc : souvenirs d'un Pierrot'', Caffera describes Rouffe as having created a complete language of gesture.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://helda.helsinki.fi/bitstream/handle/10138/33937/Acta_Scenica_25.pdf.txt;jsessionid=FC0BEFC9BD1A8E6916D4599828CD0AE6?sequence=2 | title=The Techniques of Gesture Language | publisher=The Theatre Academy Helsinki (doctoral thesis) | date=2011 | accessdate=16 May 2014 | author=Tångeberg-Grischin, Maya}}</ref>

